<DOC><DOCNO> AP880401-0290 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0200EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   04-01 0455</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0476</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Wall Street ``whiz kid'' David Bloom has pleadedguilty to mail and securities fraud charges, admitting to an artwork shopping spree funded with $10 million bilked from scores ofinvestors.   Bloom, 23, faces five years in prison and fines up to double theamount lost by investors. He told a federal judge Thursday he spentinvestors' money on ``art, automobiles, two homes and furnishings.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   House and Senate negotiators reached tentativeagreement on a sweeping trade bill designed to open foreignmarkets, but only after loading it with provisions that lawmakerssaid could invite a veto.   Repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies, tough tradesanctions against Toshiba Corp. of Japan and millions of dollars innew subsidies designed to boost U.S. grain exports were tentativelyincluded in the legislation approved Thursday evening.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Italian government has agreed to explorepossible collaboration in building the ``super collider'' atomsmasher planned by the Energy Department, Energy Secretary JohnHerrington says.   Italy has not agreed to contribute to the cost of the $4.4billion installation, but collaboration could still lead tosavings, officials said Thursday.   Italy has a distinguished history in advanced physics researchgoing back to nuclear pioneer Enrico Fermi in the 1930s.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committeehas proposed creation of a regulatory committee to oversee thenation's financial markets in the wake of the October stock marketcrash.   The bill, sponsored by Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., is beingpushed by former New Jersey Sen. Nicholas Brady, who headed apresidential task force that studied the crash.   The bill creates an Intermarket Coordination Committee composedof the chairmen of the Federal Reserve, Securities and ExchangeCommission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, officialssaid Thursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Teamsters union and the trucking industryhave reached tentative agreement on a three-year national freightcontract covering 200,000 drivers and warehouse workers.   The new agreement, unless rejected by at least two-thirds of theaffected union members, will replace a contract that expired atmidnight Thursday.   Terms of the accord were not disclosed Thursday. Includingfringe and pension benefits, the industry had calculated its totallabor costs to date at $23 an hour.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.94 to 1,988.06Thursday, finishing the week with a gain of 9.11 points.   The dollar fell slightly against major currencies.   Bond prices were narrowly mixed as the yield on the benchmark30-year Treasury bond slipped to 8.74 percent.   The contract for June delivery of live hogs plunged, and crudeoil prices were mostly unchanged.</TEXT></DOC>